  "prompt": "Is it a felony to launder money?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is a serious criminal offense and is classified as a felony in most jurisdictions, including the United States. Money laundering involves the process of making illegally-gained proceeds (such as from drug trafficking, fraud, or other criminal activities) appear legitimate by passing them through a complex sequence of banking transfers or commercial transactions.\n\nIn the U.S., money laundering is punishable under federal law, primarily under the **Money Laundering Control Act of 1986** (18 U.S.C. \u00a7 1956 and \u00a7 1957). Penalties for money laundering can include:\n\n- Substantial fines (often reaching hundreds of thousands or even millions of dollars).\n- Imprprisonment for up to 20 years per count, depending on the severity of the offense.\n- Forfeiture of assets involved in or derived from the illegal activity.\n\nState laws also criminalize money laundering and impose similar penalties. Additionally, international efforts, such as those coordinated by the **Financial Action Task Force (FATF)**, aim to combat money laundering globally.\n\nIf you or someone you know is facing allegations of money laundering, it is crucial to seek legal counsel immediately, as the consequences can be severe.",
